No, but thank you very much to the meeting organizers and the scientific

10
00:00:28.340 --> 00:00:31.820
committees for including this session in this year's very

11
00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:33.540
exciting, very interesting meeting.

12
00:00:33.970 --> 00:00:37.880
The title of the session is "Advances in Hemologic Malignancies:

13
00:00:38.300 --> 00:00:42.280
Population Sciences for Hematological Malignancies."

14
00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:46.320
So genetically, as we all know, all humans are very

15
00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:50.220
similar but not identical in our genetic makeup,

16
00:00:50.420 --> 00:00:54.170
and much of this variation that distinguishes us is the

17
00:00:54.220 --> 00:00:56.560
result of differences in ancestry.

18
00:00:57.580 --> 00:01:01.440
While most variants are evolutionarily neutral, it's well known

19
00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:05.340
that genetic variation can be associated with differences

20
00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:07.620
in wellness and illness.

21
00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:13.160
In this population sciences session, we're going to spotlight

22
00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:17.420
genetic ancestry as one factor that is associated with

23
00:01:17.460 --> 00:01:20.800
differences in the etiology and outcomes of hematologic

24
00:01:20.860 --> 00:01:24.710
malignancies among diverse populations, and

25
00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:28.100
we will also consider how genetic studies that incorporate

26
00:01:28.120 --> 00:01:32.040
individuals of diverse ancestries are helping to explain

27
00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:33.760
the observed clinical differences.

28
00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:38.360
In our first talk, I'm going to discuss diversity writ large

29
00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:40.370
and its influence on genetic studies.

30
00:01:41.180 --> 00:01:44.590
I'm also going to discuss how we at Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer

31
00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:48.340
Center are building the infrastructure to facilitate future

32
00:01:48.420 --> 00:01:50.060
studies of diversity in cancer.

33
00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:54.360
Then Dr. Anne Katherine Eisfeldt from the Ohio State

34
00:01:54.440 --> 00:01:57.220
University will present her work on genetic studies

35
00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:01.260
leveraging diversity to understand the biology and

36
00:02:01.380 --> 00:02:04.640
outcomes in AML. Then finally, Dr.

37
00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:09.039
Nick Panunzio from UC Irvine is going to discuss his work on

38
00:02:09.081 --> 00:02:11.420
genetics and ALL in Hispanics.

39
00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:16.240
If there's time after all of us have presented, we will open the

40
00:02:16.300 --> 00:02:18.130
floor to a general discussion.

41
00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:22.730
On behalf of all of us here on the bimah,

42
00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:27.930
I hope that you enjoy the session. So thanks very much, and let's get

43
00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:31.680
started. Okay. May we have the first slide

44
00:02:31.740 --> 00:02:32.450
presentation?

45
00:02:37.420 --> 00:02:41.400
All right. So thank you. So again,

46
00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:45.300
I'm Ken Onel. I'm from Roswell Park, and I'm going to be talking

47
00:02:45.420 --> 00:02:49.020
about work that we've been doing at Roswell Park to enable these genetic

48
00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:49.580
studies.

49
00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:53.800
So I have no conflicts to disclose, sadly.

50
00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Please feel free to change that after the meeting.

51
00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:01.020
Let's start by thinking about polymorphic variations.

52
00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:04.840
So this is a map of the world from

53
00:03:04.900 --> 00:03:08.360
the Thousand Genomes Project from Goncalo Abecasis'

54
00:03:08.680 --> 00:03:09.060
paper.

55
00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:13.650
And what we see is that if we look at the gray boxes,

56
00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:17.730
we see that most polymorphic variation is

57
00:03:17.780 --> 00:03:20.700
common across multiple populations.

58
00:03:21.180 --> 00:03:24.280
But in the colored boxes, what we see is that there are

59
00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:28.140
considerable polymorphic variation that is

60
00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:30.120
unique to different populations.

61
00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:34.280
The consequence of this, of course, is that there

62
00:03:34.340 --> 00:03:37.690
may be population-based differences in

63
00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:41.840
wellness and illness. And of course, this is well known to be the case.

64
00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:46.380
So now if we look at population diversity in a different

65
00:03:46.460 --> 00:03:49.720
way using linkage disequilibrium, we see

66
00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:52.660
again differences among populations.

67
00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:56.260
So here are three regions of the genome that were

68
00:03:56.440 --> 00:04:00.100
genotyped in 12 different populations.

69
00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:04.080
And what we can see is that this is now looking at

70
00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:07.960
patterns of linkage disequilibrium or correlations among

71
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:08.440
variants

72
00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:12.520
as a function of space in the genome.

73
00:04:12.560 --> 00:04:16.500
And what we see is that in newer populations, there are large

74
00:04:16.601 --> 00:04:19.750
regions of the genome that travel together,

75
00:04:20.399 --> 00:04:23.280
whereas in older populations such as African

76
00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:27.130
populations, those regions of

77
00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:30.900
linkage disequilibrium break down, and the linkage blocks are

78
00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:33.700
considerably different and smaller.

79
00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:38.160
A consequence of this difference in linkage

80
00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:41.800
disequilibrium is patterns of LD

81
00:04:41.860 --> 00:04:44.120
across regions in different populations.

82
00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:47.600
So here is a single region that has been

83
00:04:47.680 --> 00:04:51.380
characterized in first European ancestry individuals

84
00:04:51.780 --> 00:04:55.520
and then two different African admixed populations.

85
00:04:55.550 --> 00:04:59.360
And what we see is that while the variants in this

86
00:04:59.420 --> 00:05:03.290
region in Europeans are highly correlated with each other,

87
00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:07.440
that pattern of correlation breaks

88
00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:10.450
down and is quite different in

89
00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:13.600
Afro-German and Afro-Caribbean populations.

90
00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:17.760
So we took advantage of these differences in

91
00:05:18.620 --> 00:05:21.560
LD to perform a multiethnic

92
00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:27.340
genome-wide association study in pediatric B-lineage ALL.

93
00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.700
We did our discovery and our replication in European ancestry

94
00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:35.340
individuals, and we identified a novel association at

95
00:05:35.360 --> 00:05:37.990
chromosome 9.21.3.

96
00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:42.740
Then if we look across the region, we see that in

97
00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:46.930
individuals of European ancestry, our discovery and replication

98
00:05:47.060 --> 00:05:50.460
sets and Hispanic ancestry, the

99
00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:54.180
region isHighly correlated. These

100
00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:56.560
SNPs in the region are highly correlated

101
00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:00.580
with each other with an R squared of greater than 0.6.

102
00:06:01.080 --> 00:06:04.640
That LD structure breaks down in African

103
00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:07.580
ancestry individuals. So what we did was we

104
00:06:07.620 --> 00:06:11.260
genotyped these variants in all three

105
00:06:11.360 --> 00:06:14.580
ancestry individuals and performed a regional association study.

106
00:06:15.080 --> 00:06:19.040
And what we saw is that in African individuals, the only SNP that was

107
00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:21.560
associated was a different SNP,

108
00:06:21.780 --> 00:06:25.619
RS662463. And so if you look at the

109
00:06:25.660 --> 00:06:29.210
region, what you see is that in Europeans and

110
00:06:29.380 --> 00:06:33.180
in Hispanic individuals, this SNP

111
00:06:33.680 --> 00:06:36.200
and the lead SNP comprise a single

112
00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:41.680
highly correlated region, whereas in African ancestry

113
00:06:41.740 --> 00:06:45.430
individuals, that correlation, that haplotype structure,

114
00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:49.320
breaks down. And so what we were able to do then is by taking

115
00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:53.300
advantage of these differences in LD across populations, go

116
00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:57.220
from a tagging SNP identified in European individuals to a

117
00:06:57.260 --> 00:07:00.880
putative functional SNP identified in African ancestry

118
00:07:00.940 --> 00:07:04.360
individuals. And then in the study, we went along to

119
00:07:04.400 --> 00:07:07.760
demonstrate that in fact this variant is the true

120
00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:11.560
functional risk allele predisposing to B lineage ALL

121
00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:14.440
by disrupting a transcription finder binding site for

122
00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:19.580
CEBPB that ultimately resulted in lower levels

123
00:07:19.620 --> 00:07:22.980
of CD and TB binding. Expression rather.

124
00:07:23.520 --> 00:07:27.400
So that's one example of how we use differences in

125
00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:31.160
ancestry to go from tags to functional variants in

126
00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:35.080
genetic studies. But I want to turn back to where we started,

127
00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:38.740
which is thinking about differences, variation

128
00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:42.100
in ancestry, and how that might relate to

129
00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:45.310
differences in cancer etiology,

130
00:07:45.560 --> 00:07:49.060
architecture, and outcomes. So if we think about the

131
00:07:49.100 --> 00:07:52.860
genetics of different populations as being slightly different,

132
00:07:53.260 --> 00:07:57.100
those differences in variation may have implications

133
00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:01.160
for cancer phenotypes. And in fact, it turns out that this

134
00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:02.400
is, of course, true.

135
00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:07.080
And we're going to hear more about this over the course of the remainder of the

136
00:08:07.180 --> 00:08:07.620
session.

137
00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:12.200
So here in heme malignancies are studies showing that

138
00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:15.540
genetic ancestry is associated with survival

139
00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:19.719
in T lineage ALL. Here's another study

140
00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:23.620
in childhood acute lymphoblastic anemia, again showing that

141
00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:27.400
ancestry is associated with differences in molecular subtypes.

142
00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:31.280
And here from MSK is a study showing that ancestry is

143
00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:34.720
associated with the genomic architecture, the

144
00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:38.441
landscape of cancers across essentially all cancer

145
00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:42.380
types. So indeed, ancestry influences cancer

146
00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:43.120
phenotypes.

147
00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:48.140
But I want us to think about this in a little bit more nuanced of a

148
00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:52.100
way. So to be sure, variation in

149
00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:55.310
genetic ancestry will influence cancer phenotypes,

150
00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:59.620
but cancer is a complex trait resulting from the actions and the

151
00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:02.460
interactions of genetic factors and non-genetic factors.

152
00:09:02.890 --> 00:09:06.060
And so if we think about variation in

153
00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:08.129
environment exposures.

154
00:09:08.980 --> 00:09:10.800
If we think about

155
00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:16.440
individuals who are or are not exposed to different

156
00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:20.800
etiologic cancer-causing exposures, smoking, differences in

157
00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:22.620
diet, chemicals, radiation.

158
00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:28.080
Yes or no. Those exposures will activate different

159
00:09:28.140 --> 00:09:31.940
pathways. And if there's heterogeneity in the pathways

160
00:09:31.960 --> 00:09:35.600
and heterogeneity in our exposure, the inevitable consequence

161
00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:39.680
of this morass of heterogeneity and

162
00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:43.580
diversity is that we're going to attenuate our overall

163
00:09:43.590 --> 00:09:44.500
genetic signals.

164
00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:46.040
So

165
00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:50.310
the point then is that diversity in genetic studies,

166
00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:52.980
to be sure, includes

167
00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:57.600
genetic diversity and ancestry, but it's a whole lot more.

168
00:09:58.380 --> 00:10:01.920
So race, ethnicity, sex, gender, social economic

169
00:10:01.940 --> 00:10:02.500
status,

170
00:10:03.400 --> 00:10:06.840
social determinants of health, rural, urban environments.

171
00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:09.480
Completely different sets of exposures, of course.

172
00:10:09.879 --> 00:10:13.280
Exposure to smoking or alcohol, diet, nutrition,

173
00:10:13.319 --> 00:10:17.120
obesity, infections, and so on and so forth.

174
00:10:17.540 --> 00:10:21.260
So the point is that there's a lot of diversity that is

175
00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:24.780
not reflected exclusively in the context of

176
00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:28.620
ancestry, but that clearly acts and interacts

177
00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:32.600
with core differences in diversity to result in

178
00:10:32.660 --> 00:10:36.610
diversity in tumor etiology, tumor architecture, and mutation

179
00:10:36.700 --> 00:10:39.310
signatures, and of course, clinical outcomes.

180
00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:43.820
So let's think of an example to sort of make that

181
00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:47.760
case. So Hodgkin lymphoma. Here's a study that was

182
00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:51.760
performed by Wendy Cozen and Tom Mack looking at

183
00:10:51.820 --> 00:10:55.760
pairs of MZ and DZ twins. And what they found

184
00:10:56.180 --> 00:10:59.980
is that the concordance of the developing of

185
00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:03.860
Hodgkin lymphoma in MZ twins was markedly higher

186
00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:08.160
than in DZ twins. Since that's controlling for environment, the

187
00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:11.380
conclusion is that Hodgkin lymphoma is a highly

188
00:11:11.500 --> 00:11:15.480
genetically determined trait. Here, though, in

189
00:11:15.560 --> 00:11:19.300
a later study from 2009 by Wendy and Tom again,

190
00:11:19.780 --> 00:11:23.220
what we see is that in twins that are

191
00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:25.720
discordant for Hodgkin's phenotype,

192
00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:30.360
then we see differences in exposures,

193
00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:33.420
specifically fecal-oral exposures, suggesting...

194
00:11:33.920 --> 00:11:37.860
And the significance is quite profound

195
00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:41.220
with an odds ratio that is lowered by half.

196
00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:45.520
So the point is that even highly genetically determined traits are

197
00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:47.920
highly modified by non-genetic factors.

198
00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:51.440
And so we really need to think about these two

199
00:11:51.560 --> 00:11:53.440
sources of diversity in

200
00:11:53.500 --> 00:11:55.996
concertSo really,

201
00:11:56.816 --> 00:12:00.676
I think one of the only studies that attempted to control for

202
00:12:00.696 --> 00:12:04.176
diversity in ancestry and diversity in exposure

203
00:12:04.656 --> 00:12:08.276
was one that we did a few years ago, looking at second cancer,

204
00:12:08.556 --> 00:12:12.436
again, after Hodgkin lymphoma, in which we tried to control for both

205
00:12:12.476 --> 00:12:14.556
genetic and non-genetic diversity.

206
00:12:14.596 --> 00:12:18.536
The idea is that Hodgkin lymphoma is highly associated with

207
00:12:18.576 --> 00:12:20.956
exposure to radiation to the chest.

208
00:12:21.036 --> 00:12:24.736
The second cancers that we see are largely breast cancers and

209
00:12:24.796 --> 00:12:25.796
thyroid cancers.

210
00:12:26.835 --> 00:12:30.456
The occurrence of these radiation-induced second cancers is inversely

211
00:12:30.536 --> 00:12:34.396
correlated with age. So if you're treated for Hodgkin lymphoma under age

212
00:12:34.616 --> 00:12:38.476
20, you're very high risk for these radiation-induced second cancers.

213
00:12:38.556 --> 00:12:40.316
Over 20, you're at a much lower risk.

214
00:12:41.516 --> 00:12:45.236
The point is that this is also a very important clinical phenotype, and it's

215
00:12:45.256 --> 00:12:48.976
responsible for about 20% of mortality in Hodgkin

216
00:12:49.016 --> 00:12:51.556
lymphoma survivors. So it's profound.

217
00:12:51.696 --> 00:12:55.536
Now, the key point of the study is by virtue of

218
00:12:55.576 --> 00:12:58.336
controlling for both exposure and ancestry,

219
00:12:59.196 --> 00:13:03.176
we were able to do a well-powered study with a very limited

220
00:13:03.256 --> 00:13:06.836
number of cases and controls. So just 96 cases and

221
00:13:06.936 --> 00:13:10.616
82 controls. This was done in collaboration with a childhood

222
00:13:10.716 --> 00:13:14.556
cancer survivor study. We identified

223
00:13:14.636 --> 00:13:16.496
two regions that were associated

224
00:13:17.376 --> 00:13:20.096
with these radiation-induced second cancers.

225
00:13:20.176 --> 00:13:23.996
We performed a replication analysis, and we were able to replicate

226
00:13:24.036 --> 00:13:27.896
the findings on chromosome 6. It turns out

227
00:13:28.256 --> 00:13:31.936
that the region was intragenic between a gene called

228
00:13:31.976 --> 00:13:33.056
ATG5, which

229
00:13:34.356 --> 00:13:38.116
functions in autophagy, and a gene called PRDM1, which is

230
00:13:38.176 --> 00:13:41.996
also known as BLIMP1, which is a transcriptional repressor

231
00:13:42.006 --> 00:13:45.996
that is often mutated, actually somatically, in non-Hodgkin's

232
00:13:46.016 --> 00:13:49.636
lymphoma. We then performed functional studies with cell

233
00:13:49.676 --> 00:13:53.136
lines that were either homozygous for the protective

234
00:13:53.376 --> 00:13:56.116
variant or homozygous for the risk variant.

235
00:13:56.176 --> 00:13:59.656
And you can see here western blots following radiation

236
00:13:59.696 --> 00:14:03.536
exposure, and this is reflected as well in these

237
00:14:03.576 --> 00:14:07.235
graphs, that there's both significantly increased baseline

238
00:14:07.276 --> 00:14:10.036
levels of PRDM1 following

239
00:14:10.856 --> 00:14:14.636
in cells that were homozygous for the protective

240
00:14:14.676 --> 00:14:16.376
allele as compared to the risk allele.

241
00:14:16.896 --> 00:14:20.576
And again, in cells homozygous for the protective allele,

242
00:14:20.896 --> 00:14:24.436
there was significant induction following radiation exposure.

243
00:14:24.516 --> 00:14:28.376
So the point is that we were able to start with a

244
00:14:28.436 --> 00:14:32.256
well-controlled experiment, a very small number of cases and controls,

245
00:14:32.656 --> 00:14:36.265
and then go to function that was

246
00:14:36.316 --> 00:14:40.176
associated with this

247
00:14:41.316 --> 00:14:41.916
phenotype.

248
00:14:43.056 --> 00:14:47.006
And really underscoring how important this result is,

249
00:14:47.436 --> 00:14:51.056
if we look at individuals who are homozygous

250
00:14:51.396 --> 00:14:54.896
for the protective allele by

251
00:14:55.336 --> 00:14:58.476
20 years after exposure to radiation, only about

252
00:14:58.716 --> 00:15:02.446
3% had been diagnosed with some of these

253
00:15:02.476 --> 00:15:06.396
radiation-induced second cancers, whereas individuals who are homozygous

254
00:15:06.456 --> 00:15:10.226
for the risk allele, it's 30%. So that is an incredibly

255
00:15:10.236 --> 00:15:12.716
profound difference resulting from one

256
00:15:12.776 --> 00:15:16.596
variant that lives at the intersection of

257
00:15:16.636 --> 00:15:18.796
genes and environment. So

258
00:15:19.736 --> 00:15:23.716
I really like this example because it really underscores how important this

259
00:15:23.796 --> 00:15:24.956
is. So

260
00:15:26.076 --> 00:15:29.836
