BRCA mutations convey risk for heme malignancies, but those patients are often

516
00:30:38.388 --> 00:30:40.668
in breast cancer genetic studies.

517
00:30:40.728 --> 00:30:43.708
So how do you account for all of this new messiness that we're living in?

518
00:30:44.208 --> 00:30:46.768
Right. So I just want to make sure I heard your question.

519
00:30:47.118 --> 00:30:47.118
Yeah.

520
00:30:47.168 --> 00:30:50.128
So the question has to do with the clinical genomics department.

521
00:30:50.348 --> 00:30:50.428
Yeah.

522
00:30:50.588 --> 00:30:54.118
How does that incorporate patients from across the institution-

523
00:30:54.628 --> 00:30:54.638
Yeah

524
00:30:54.638 --> 00:30:58.228
... coming from different places who might have different predispositions.

525
00:30:58.238 --> 00:30:58.238
Yeah.

526
00:30:58.248 --> 00:30:58.808
Is that right?

527
00:30:59.048 --> 00:30:59.588
That's right.

528
00:30:59.648 --> 00:31:02.848
Okay. So, it's actually incredibly simple.

529
00:31:03.028 --> 00:31:06.948
What we do is we empower genetic testing across the

530
00:31:06.988 --> 00:31:09.368
different departments, done at point of care,

531
00:31:10.228 --> 00:31:13.848
and we make it so that every patient gets tested.

532
00:31:14.088 --> 00:31:17.328
Right? And then the requirement is that any

533
00:31:17.448 --> 00:31:20.968
patient who has a positive genetic finding gets

534
00:31:21.068 --> 00:31:24.288
referred to clinical genomics, the medicine service.

535
00:31:25.008 --> 00:31:28.708
But also because our colleagues aren't comfortable discussing

536
00:31:28.848 --> 00:31:32.688
even things like variants of uncertain significance, which typically are

537
00:31:32.748 --> 00:31:35.328
not used clinically. There are, of course, exceptions.

538
00:31:36.388 --> 00:31:39.588
We see all of them as well. Okay? The

539
00:31:40.068 --> 00:31:44.048
individuals who have true pathogenic variants come to see

540
00:31:44.248 --> 00:31:47.768
us in the medicine service. The individuals who

541
00:31:47.828 --> 00:31:51.748
have variants of uncertain significance are initially seen

542
00:31:51.808 --> 00:31:54.928
by members of our counseling team, and then based

543
00:31:54.968 --> 00:31:55.828
upon

544
00:31:56.848 --> 00:32:00.478
their assessment of both the likelihood that a variant of

545
00:32:00.508 --> 00:32:04.288
uncertain significance may or may not be pathogenic, and of

546
00:32:04.368 --> 00:32:08.348
course, the family history as well, they either do or don't refer

547
00:32:08.388 --> 00:32:11.948
them to clinical genomics, the medicine service, for ongoing

548
00:32:12.068 --> 00:32:12.548
follow-up.

549
00:32:13.108 --> 00:32:13.888
Great. Thank you.

550
00:32:17.168 --> 00:32:17.178
Okay.

551
00:32:17.208 --> 00:32:21.108
Hi. Tim Lei, WashU. Thanks, Ken. It's a really interesting

552
00:32:22.548 --> 00:32:26.308
paradigm you set up here. One question, though, about race and ethnicity

553
00:32:26.508 --> 00:32:30.088
and economic diversity. So a lot of these things are very

554
00:32:30.128 --> 00:32:33.208
significant issues in terms of enrollment in studies like this.

555
00:32:33.528 --> 00:32:33.708
Yeah.

556
00:32:34.188 --> 00:32:35.568
A cancer center has to help.

557
00:32:36.648 --> 00:32:37.988
I don't think you can do it alone.

558
00:32:38.098 --> 00:32:38.098
Yeah.

559
00:32:38.128 --> 00:32:41.768
But what kinds of programs are in place in your

560
00:32:41.828 --> 00:32:45.688
cancer center to help include those diverse groups

561
00:32:45.748 --> 00:32:46.188
and get them-

562
00:32:46.308 --> 00:32:46.318
Right

563
00:32:46.318 --> 00:32:47.548
... to participate in these trials?

564
00:32:48.028 --> 00:32:50.728
Right. So that's an incredibly important question.

565
00:32:51.448 --> 00:32:55.068
And that's why I actually highlighted the fact that as of right now,

566
00:32:55.988 --> 00:32:59.548
over 80% of people who are approached to consent

567
00:32:59.868 --> 00:33:00.848
are consenting.

568
00:33:02.108 --> 00:33:04.728
So we seem to be succeeding.

569
00:33:04.968 --> 00:33:08.837
Where we're sort of driving-

570
00:33:08.837 --> 00:33:09.978
Why only 80%?

571
00:33:10.408 --> 00:33:10.728
I'm sorry?

572
00:33:11.048 --> 00:33:12.318
Why only 80%?

573
00:33:12.488 --> 00:33:15.868
No, you're right. I'd love for it to be 100%.

574
00:33:15.897 --> 00:33:15.897
Yeah.

575
00:33:16.588 --> 00:33:18.348
The way that we're thinking about it...

576
00:33:18.808 --> 00:33:22.348
So I have to also add that I've only been at Roswell

577
00:33:22.548 --> 00:33:25.808
for less than two years, and these are all new programs.

578
00:33:25.908 --> 00:33:26.108
So,

579
00:33:28.248 --> 00:33:31.248
I don't believe that we have optimized things.

580
00:33:32.668 --> 00:33:34.828
To be perfectly honest, we're still figuring it out.

581
00:33:35.988 --> 00:33:38.888
Our legacy consenting process

582
00:33:39.688 --> 00:33:41.448
has been human-based.

583
00:33:42.588 --> 00:33:46.088
And we're converting to an e-consent process.

584
00:33:47.048 --> 00:33:47.628
And

585
00:33:48.428 --> 00:33:51.608
my hope is that that will help, but

586
00:33:53.068 --> 00:33:55.868
it may not. It may actually have an

587
00:33:55.968 --> 00:33:59.788
unanticipated negative effect on getting

588
00:33:59.828 --> 00:34:03.068
people to consent. So I don't know the answer to that yet.

589
00:34:03.888 --> 00:34:04.218
But in term-

590
00:34:04.228 --> 00:34:05.888
Well, it's hard, but it's a worthwhile goal.

591
00:34:06.528 --> 00:34:06.988
Say that again?

592
00:34:07.128 --> 00:34:09.247
It's hard, but it's a worthwhile goal.

593
00:34:09.569 --> 00:34:13.488
Well, that's right. And the idea is that by making

594
00:34:13.548 --> 00:34:17.508
it available to everyone, our hypothesis is that, and

595
00:34:17.569 --> 00:34:21.298
by doing things like having genetic testing performed

596
00:34:21.488 --> 00:34:25.149
at points of care and consenting done at points of care,

597
00:34:25.569 --> 00:34:29.288
we will just make it just part of the way we do business at Roswell

598
00:34:29.609 --> 00:34:32.848
and make it available to everyone. But I don't know the answer to that yet.

599
00:34:34.528 --> 00:34:34.768
Yes.

600
00:34:35.428 --> 00:34:38.998
Thanks. So are you including heme malignancies in your

601
00:34:39.528 --> 00:34:42.978
effort to be complete? And if you do, are you doing skin biopsies?

602
00:34:43.048 --> 00:34:46.248
Are you waiting till they're in remission? How do you work them in?

603
00:34:46.308 --> 00:34:48.828
This was a heme session, and that's really a challenge.

604
00:34:50.248 --> 00:34:52.428
I'm sorry, I didn't hear your question.

605
00:34:52.928 --> 00:34:53.518
Oh. Sorry.

606
00:34:53.968 --> 00:34:56.488
And it's me. I apologize for that.

607
00:34:56.589 --> 00:34:58.648
I'm sorrier.

608
00:34:59.568 --> 00:35:02.508
So what do you do with patients with heme malignancies?

609
00:35:02.588 --> 00:35:03.788
Are you including them in

610
00:35:04.968 --> 00:35:05.968
your comprehensive approach?

611
00:35:06.028 --> 00:35:06.988
Oh, 100%.

612
00:35:07.028 --> 00:35:09.088
Are you doing their skin biopsies?

613
00:35:09.108 --> 00:35:09.288
Are you-

614
00:35:09.488 --> 00:35:09.518
Yeah

615
00:35:09.548 --> 00:35:11.288
... doing them after they go into remission?

616
00:35:11.428 --> 00:35:12.008
How are you-

617
00:35:12.418 --> 00:35:12.418
Right

618
00:35:12.418 --> 00:35:13.388
... systematizing this?

619
00:35:13.528 --> 00:35:15.128
So it depends upon the patient.

620
00:35:16.048 --> 00:35:19.948
We do remission samples. We do skin biopsies

621
00:35:20.828 --> 00:35:24.228
on lots of patients who are coming to clinical genomics

622
00:35:25.808 --> 00:35:29.678
early in their diagnosis. So it really is individually based,

623
00:35:29.768 --> 00:35:31.688
but we have the capacity to do both.

624
00:35:32.368 --> 00:35:32.588
Okay.

625
00:35:34.228 --> 00:35:35.988
All right. Thank you very much.

626
00:35:37.108 --> 00:35:40.828
And I will now turn the stage over

627
00:35:40.908 --> 00:35:43.268
to Dr. Eisell with our next talk.

628
00:35:44.848 --> 00:35:47.388
Thank you.

629
00:35:56.880 --> 00:35:57.660
Thank you so much

630
00:35:58.580 --> 00:36:01.900
for coming and for the great start into the session.

631
00:36:01.980 --> 00:36:05.500
I think the build has been perfect and I'm really, really grateful for

632
00:36:05.540 --> 00:36:09.430
ACR for providing this forum. Also, special extra thank you to

633
00:36:09.440 --> 00:36:13.170
Wendy Kosan for putting the speakers and all of us in contact.

634
00:36:13.210 --> 00:36:17.000
It has been really fun to do this. I'm going to, in this

635
00:36:17.010 --> 00:36:20.360
presentation, talk mainly about acute myeloid leukemia,

636
00:36:20.940 --> 00:36:24.900
showing some of our efforts, starting really with a level-setting first on

637
00:36:24.980 --> 00:36:27.120
AML. We are all working in different fields.

638
00:36:27.140 --> 00:36:30.860
Then about what's already known, and spend the last third of the

639
00:36:30.960 --> 00:36:34.760
talk on unpublished data from multiple friends and

640
00:36:34.800 --> 00:36:36.460
collaborators from across the country.

641
00:36:37.880 --> 00:36:39.840
I have my disclosures.

642
00:36:41.580 --> 00:36:44.560
So as a level setting in here, so AML

643
00:36:45.300 --> 00:36:48.940
is classified as a disease, just as most of them,

644
00:36:49.560 --> 00:36:53.050
just based on general histology, so the blast morphology associated

645
00:36:53.120 --> 00:36:56.480
dysplasia. Then we're looking also at specific chromosomal

646
00:36:56.500 --> 00:37:00.200
abnormalities. And then really more and more on the forefront are the

647
00:37:00.220 --> 00:37:01.540
recurrent gene mutations

648
00:37:02.560 --> 00:37:05.460
that are now disease-defining and that are also

649
00:37:05.800 --> 00:37:09.160
prognosis-defining. This is an example of the European LeukemiaNet

650
00:37:09.240 --> 00:37:12.780
classification. That is one clinically used

651
00:37:12.860 --> 00:37:16.740
algorithm where we try to see which patients are more or less likely

652
00:37:16.800 --> 00:37:20.790
to respond to, in this case, conventional cytotoxic chemotherapy.

653
00:37:21.180 --> 00:37:24.640
And as you can see here, here are multiple different chromosomal aberration and

654
00:37:24.740 --> 00:37:28.560
gene mutations in here, and generally patients who are

655
00:37:28.640 --> 00:37:31.940
classified as favorable risk, say, for example, don't receive a stem cell

656
00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:33.600
transplant in first complete remission.

657
00:37:35.360 --> 00:37:39.260
I think it's good to remind ourselves how we come up with this, with the

658
00:37:39.300 --> 00:37:42.960
disease classification, but even more so European LeukemiaNet or other

659
00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:46.860
algorithms. The first thing that has to happen is that the patient has to

660
00:37:46.920 --> 00:37:49.900
present to something as large as a comprehensive cancer center

661
00:37:50.720 --> 00:37:54.420
that then enrolls this patient into biobanking and a clinical

662
00:37:54.480 --> 00:37:58.100
trial, and this was just one of the excellent questions at the end, going through

663
00:37:58.110 --> 00:38:01.750
the different filters. And this treatment site or the

664
00:38:01.820 --> 00:38:05.560
biobanking site has to be so large enough that it contributes to

665
00:38:05.600 --> 00:38:09.180
pivotal studies, and you have to have a PI

666
00:38:09.240 --> 00:38:12.809
who has to be on one of these, either informing

667
00:38:12.900 --> 00:38:16.560
sections and speaking up loud enough to actually put

668
00:38:16.740 --> 00:38:20.040
these data and their samples into these studies that are being analyzed.

669
00:38:20.680 --> 00:38:23.800
So a lot of patients are getting lost in this process.

670
00:38:26.300 --> 00:38:30.240
The ELN and other genetic algorithms work for risk

671
00:38:30.300 --> 00:38:34.280
prediction, and this is an example for AML if we classify it by

672
00:38:34.340 --> 00:38:37.460
ELN risk. But I want to point out two different things here.

673
00:38:37.660 --> 00:38:41.540
One thing is actually it's not really great that favorable prognosis

674
00:38:41.600 --> 00:38:44.580
that we predict for a 60% survival.

675
00:38:45.280 --> 00:38:48.760
This actually highlights how much room there is for improvement just in

676
00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:53.020
general in AML to improve how patients are doing, but also

677
00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:56.680
how we are predicting, which means there's a pretty big error rate and what is it

678
00:38:56.720 --> 00:39:00.380
that we have to do to even make this error

679
00:39:00.400 --> 00:39:04.100
prediction rate better. And the second thing I would like to point

680
00:39:04.200 --> 00:39:08.180
out is if we use this, and these are very small studies, if we try to use these

681
00:39:08.190 --> 00:39:12.060
algorithms on patients who are not of European ancestry, it

682
00:39:12.280 --> 00:39:16.240
really becomes less distinct. And yes, it's on the one hand for numbers, and

683
00:39:16.300 --> 00:39:19.680
on the other hand also highlighting that this might not be

684
00:39:19.820 --> 00:39:22.620
usable across other populations.

685
00:39:24.080 --> 00:39:25.120
Why could this be the case?

686
00:39:26.300 --> 00:39:30.040
Everything that we know about AML is based on several very large-scale

687
00:39:30.220 --> 00:39:31.200
studies. One of them,

688
00:39:32.260 --> 00:39:36.220
the very first one being led by Violet Tingley in the audience and the

689
00:39:36.260 --> 00:39:39.700
TCGA. We have now way over 4,000 AML patients,

690
00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:42.430
but less than 2% are non-European.

691
00:39:43.060 --> 00:39:46.980
And really pointing out that these patients were all basically treated at

692
00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:49.900
major US cancer centers or European cancer centers,

693
00:39:50.960 --> 00:39:54.860
so that there is very little diversity in anything that informs what

694
00:39:54.900 --> 00:39:58.720
we are doing. So the central hypothesis is here

695
00:39:58.980 --> 00:40:02.960
from my talk and what I really believe is that it's restricted view on AML

696
00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:06.860
genomes, and thus the biology of AML impacts our

697
00:40:06.900 --> 00:40:10.690
understanding of AML in general, because we just have been restricting

698
00:40:10.740 --> 00:40:14.430
our knowledge pool in here. So we need to increase the size and diversity of the

699
00:40:14.500 --> 00:40:18.120
patient populations. And while I'm focusing on genetic

700
00:40:18.159 --> 00:40:19.180
ancestry in this talk,

701
00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:23.520
this is not in isolation, as really Ken highlighted it out, but we have to

702
00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:26.840
also put the lived experience geography into

703
00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:27.660
consideration.

704
00:40:28.700 --> 00:40:32.340
This is a good example, and it was very sobering for me.

705
00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:36.360
This is just a molecular oncoprint done on data obtained from

706
00:40:36.400 --> 00:40:40.260
Flatiron. And while they always have to be taken with a grain of salt, we spend

707
00:40:40.320 --> 00:40:44.140
almost nine months, length of a pregnancy, to clean up this data

708
00:40:44.220 --> 00:40:47.390
set from Flatiron, so I believe it had a good quality afterwards.

709
00:40:47.980 --> 00:40:51.940
And the mutation frequency, the landscape that we see,

710
00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:55.610
is very different. Flatiron has patients who are treated in the community,

711
00:40:55.660 --> 00:40:59.340
and basically almost 60% of these patients would be

712
00:40:59.380 --> 00:41:01.540
myelodysplasia-related in their classification.

713
00:41:01.960 --> 00:41:05.540
Like everything is reversed in some parts, meaning that

714
00:41:05.620 --> 00:41:09.300
the patients who have not been enrolled in here might have changed our

715
00:41:09.360 --> 00:41:13.240
idea of what the most common, most frequent mutations in leukemia

716
00:41:13.320 --> 00:41:15.620
are if we would have taken those into consideration.

717
00:41:16.820 --> 00:41:20.700
So it means that we really have to look at this interaction of,

718
00:41:20.820 --> 00:41:24.440
on the one hand, the genetics, so the ancestry as defined by ancestry informative

719
00:41:24.540 --> 00:41:25.770
markers outlined before,

720
00:41:26.760 --> 00:41:30.420
so the constitutional genetic background, and also race ethnicity, which I think

721
00:41:30.480 --> 00:41:33.660
about as a lived experience, so everything else but shaping them in here.

722
00:41:34.340 --> 00:41:37.960
And I will try to outline when I'm referring to what in here the

723
00:41:38.020 --> 00:41:39.720
majority of studies will be

724
00:41:40.520 --> 00:41:42.420
really defined by genetic ancestry.

725
00:41:44.580 --> 00:41:48.220
So what do we know thus far how genetic ancestry

726
00:41:48.280 --> 00:41:50.760
and/or race ethnicity matters in AML?

727
00:41:51.200 --> 00:41:54.100
So there have been several studies who showed that

728
00:41:55.200 --> 00:41:59.128
both in the setting ofJust general sciences like on

729
00:41:59.148 --> 00:42:03.028
the SEER network, Black patients do significantly worse

730
00:42:03.068 --> 00:42:06.728
than white patients. And this is also true if we look at patients who were treated

731
00:42:06.848 --> 00:42:10.708
on the same frontline clinical trials of, in this case, the ALLIANCE

732
00:42:10.728 --> 00:42:14.608
cooperative study group in here. And this has just been

733
00:42:14.848 --> 00:42:18.468
shown not only in the setting of the ALLIANCE, but these are unpublished data

734
00:42:18.528 --> 00:42:22.208
provided by Irum Khan and the group in ECOG-ACRIN, where also

735
00:42:22.928 --> 00:42:26.448
Black self-reported race/ethnicity was the most important

736
00:42:26.968 --> 00:42:29.268
factor for inferior overall survival.

737
00:42:30.648 --> 00:42:34.608
And the survival disparity is not only seen in

738
00:42:34.668 --> 00:42:38.428
older patients who may have a lot of comorbidities, it's actually especially

739
00:42:38.488 --> 00:42:40.468
seen in young patients. That was shocking to me.

740
00:42:40.928 --> 00:42:44.797
So if you look at somebody who's younger than 30 years of

741
00:42:44.968 --> 00:42:47.728
age, and if this individual is Black,

742
00:42:48.968 --> 00:42:52.788
there's an almost 12-year shorter overall survival in here,

743
00:42:52.908 --> 00:42:56.828
median overall survival. And it's a combination of maybe a

744
00:42:56.868 --> 00:43:00.508
delayed diagnosis. As you can see here, there are a lot of early deaths, but also a

745
00:43:00.548 --> 00:43:02.018
very low complete remission rate,

746
00:43:02.928 --> 00:43:06.288
highlighting that there's probably really a biologic rationale because all these

747
00:43:06.308 --> 00:43:07.778
patients made it to a clinical trial.

748
00:43:08.048 --> 00:43:11.248
They were all in the hospital, and they're still not responding to the treatment as

749
00:43:11.288 --> 00:43:11.688
they should.

750
00:43:13.568 --> 00:43:17.488
The third finding, and just as we all know, is

751
00:43:17.548 --> 00:43:20.798
just highlighting and putting it in here is that, of course, the socioeconomic

752
00:43:20.868 --> 00:43:24.748
factors impact on the survival. This is a study done by

753
00:43:24.788 --> 00:43:28.688
Jesse Blassack, and Electa Paskett, where they use zip codes

754
00:43:28.748 --> 00:43:32.568
as we can do it here, sadly, to assign a sociodemographic

755
00:43:32.648 --> 00:43:36.498
index. And what you could see is that patients who have higher

756
00:43:36.548 --> 00:43:39.768
social disparity index, they do poorly.

757
00:43:40.108 --> 00:43:43.948
But the second thing on this side is that if you're Black

758
00:43:44.868 --> 00:43:48.808
and have a high SDI index, you do even worse than white patients

759
00:43:48.848 --> 00:43:50.908
in exactly the same sociodemographic group.

760
00:43:51.448 --> 00:43:54.988
And, I think it's also notable to mention that there are,

761
00:43:55.228 --> 00:43:58.968
unfortunately in the study, not enough Black individuals who are

762
00:43:59.008 --> 00:44:00.388
classified as SDI low.

763
00:44:02.348 --> 00:44:06.308
There are differences in the frequencies of the known genes

764
00:44:06.328 --> 00:44:07.988
that we are testing every day in clinic.

765
