1069
01:02:02.276 --> 01:02:05.236
So what I'm really going to focus on here is a specific subtype of acute

1070
01:02:05.256 --> 01:02:08.056
lymphoblastic leukemia, PH-like ALL.

1071
01:02:08.716 --> 01:02:12.326
For those in the audience likely are familiar with this, this was a subtype that

1072
01:02:12.376 --> 01:02:15.906
was co-discovered by Charles Mulligan, who continues to work on this, as well as

1073
01:02:15.936 --> 01:02:18.016
several labs at MD Anderson and in Penn.

1074
01:02:18.756 --> 01:02:22.356
And essentially, it gets its name by the fact that it shares several of the same

1075
01:02:22.396 --> 01:02:25.996
characteristics as Ph-plus or Philadelphia chromosome-plus

1076
01:02:26.036 --> 01:02:29.236
ALL, but lacks that BCR-ABL1 chromosome.

1077
01:02:29.676 --> 01:02:33.506
And they're actually very genetically heterogeneous, but one thing that really ties

1078
01:02:33.516 --> 01:02:37.296
a lot of them together is that over 60% of them have overexpression of this

1079
01:02:37.316 --> 01:02:41.036
CRLF2, which encodes one half of this TSLP

1080
01:02:41.076 --> 01:02:43.456
receptor, which drives JAK-STAT pathway.

1081
01:02:43.516 --> 01:02:47.496
So one way this is actually diagnosed is by seeing excess CRLF2 on the cell

1082
01:02:47.556 --> 01:02:51.056
surface of these. So what's leading to this excess CRLF2

1083
01:02:51.496 --> 01:02:54.756
expression? It's actually one of two common

1084
01:02:55.236 --> 01:02:59.216
genome rearrangements. So one is a translocation with chromosome 14,

1085
01:02:59.736 --> 01:03:03.716
where a double-strand break is induced on the RAG complex during VDJ

1086
01:03:03.776 --> 01:03:07.736
recombination. And then another double-strand break is induced on the X

1087
01:03:07.756 --> 01:03:09.556
or Y chromosome with the CRLF2 locus.

1088
01:03:10.025 --> 01:03:13.516
And this puts the Mu enhancer in close proximity to CRLF2, leading to

1089
01:03:13.556 --> 01:03:17.516
overexpression. The other rearrangement is an interstitial deletion on the X

1090
01:03:17.636 --> 01:03:21.296
or Y chromosome, where two double-strand breaks near CRLF2 and

1091
01:03:21.376 --> 01:03:25.096
P2RY8 occur, leading to a deletion of the intervening sequence.

1092
01:03:25.936 --> 01:03:29.266
What's really interesting about these is that even though a large percentage have

1093
01:03:29.266 --> 01:03:32.776
these CRLF2 mutations, a lot of extra mutations are additionally

1094
01:03:32.816 --> 01:03:36.806
associated with this cancer, especially JAK2 mutations and other

1095
01:03:36.836 --> 01:03:38.396
mutations in IKZF1.

1096
01:03:40.745 --> 01:03:44.656
And what we've really found when we've studied this is that these PH-like ALLs

1097
01:03:44.696 --> 01:03:48.656
are very genetically unstable. So we've actually done long-read sequencing

1098
01:03:48.716 --> 01:03:52.596
on patients that have Ph-plus or PH-like, and remarkably from these Circos

1099
01:03:52.616 --> 01:03:55.036
plots, we can see that in the Ph-plus we see that

1100
01:03:55.876 --> 01:03:57.796
Philadelphia chromosome very clearly.

1101
01:03:57.816 --> 01:04:01.066
But in the PH-like, we see in addition to the CRLF2 rearrangement,

1102
01:04:01.696 --> 01:04:04.716
several other rearrangements and deletions throughout the genome, and you can

1103
01:04:04.756 --> 01:04:08.036
appreciate that too from these chromosome spreads.

1104
01:04:10.396 --> 01:04:13.596
So if you're familiar with this disease, you also likely know that it's associated

1105
01:04:13.636 --> 01:04:17.036
with a cancer disparity in people that identify as being Hispanic or

1106
01:04:17.076 --> 01:04:20.736
Latino. So this is a study from a cohort of patients at MD

1107
01:04:20.796 --> 01:04:24.766
Anderson, where they actually looked at the PH-like ALL and found that nearly

1108
01:04:24.936 --> 01:04:28.906
70% of the cases that they saw there are from

1109
01:04:28.936 --> 01:04:31.156
people that identify as Hispanic or Latino.

1110
01:04:31.166 --> 01:04:34.965
And if you look at those specifically, a large percent, almost 80%,

1111
01:04:35.056 --> 01:04:38.876
had this CRLF2 rearrangement. And so it seems that there's something about the

1112
01:04:38.896 --> 01:04:42.516
CRLF2 rearrangement that makes this a more aggressive treatment refractory cancer

1113
01:04:42.875 --> 01:04:46.495
and is also driving this health disparity in this Hispanic and Latino population.

1114
01:04:48.276 --> 01:04:51.776
So kind of really where I came into this is genome instability was kind of my

1115
01:04:51.836 --> 01:04:55.116
training and my background, and that's what my real interest was, trying to figure

1116
01:04:55.136 --> 01:04:56.956
out the etiology of this mechanism.

1117
01:04:56.976 --> 01:05:00.196
And just as a quick primer, just want to kind of go into some of the things that we

1118
01:05:00.236 --> 01:05:02.276
have found associated with this cancer.

1119
01:05:02.516 --> 01:05:05.706
But essentially, we knew one of the things that was happening was this

1120
01:05:05.716 --> 01:05:09.556
double-strand break on chromosome 14, but we're really interested in the CRLF2

1121
01:05:09.576 --> 01:05:12.796
double-strand break and what's causing that. Just want to skip ahead here.

1122
01:05:13.536 --> 01:05:16.786
A major clue from that came from work from Michael Lieber's lab, who did a lot of

1123
01:05:16.816 --> 01:05:20.756
work studying another translocation with IGH PCL2.

1124
01:05:21.276 --> 01:05:24.736
And what he found is that if you actually sequence the translocation junctions from

1125
01:05:24.816 --> 01:05:27.656
several of these different patients, shown here as these triangles,

1126
01:05:28.536 --> 01:05:31.356
at PCL2, they seem to cluster in very tight regions.

1127
01:05:31.876 --> 01:05:34.286
And they all seem to cluster around these CpG sites.

1128
01:05:34.796 --> 01:05:38.576
And so what's significant about that is that these CpG sites are actually motifs

1129
01:05:38.586 --> 01:05:42.516
that are recognized by activation-induced cytidine deaminase, which is one of the

1130
01:05:42.556 --> 01:05:43.196
common motifs

1131
01:05:44.116 --> 01:05:47.916
other than WGCW sites. And while you're likely familiar with AID

1132
01:05:48.056 --> 01:05:51.936
as being common in germinal centers, where it's highly expressed to drive

1133
01:05:51.976 --> 01:05:55.826
somatic hypermutation and class switch recombination, there is evidence showing

1134
01:05:55.856 --> 01:05:59.656
that it can have leaky expression in immature B cells concurrent with VDJ

1135
01:05:59.676 --> 01:06:02.866
recombination. And they've done some really interesting work to kind of show that

1136
01:06:02.896 --> 01:06:05.246
this is the etiology of that translocation.

1137
01:06:06.316 --> 01:06:09.596
And so kind of going back to the model that we're putting forth, we wanted to test

1138
01:06:09.616 --> 01:06:12.656
to see if a similar thing was happening with CRLF2 IGH

1139
01:06:12.696 --> 01:06:16.396
translocations. Where in normal B cells, we would have the RAG complex

1140
01:06:16.736 --> 01:06:19.556
leading to VDJ and CRLF2 is unperturbed.

1141
01:06:20.276 --> 01:06:24.256
Whereas in this state here you would have sporadic AID expression leading

1142
01:06:24.336 --> 01:06:26.636
to additional breaks at CRLF2 driving this

1143
01:06:26.656 --> 01:06:30.556
rearrangement.And so in order

1144
01:06:30.596 --> 01:06:34.196
to delve into this, what we actually did was we developed an innovative digital

1145
01:06:34.476 --> 01:06:37.516
PCR assay to actually interrogate the sequences of

1146
01:06:37.556 --> 01:06:41.396
CRLF2. And we can do this both in cell lines and in

1147
01:06:41.436 --> 01:06:43.816
human patients, which is shown in this study shown here.

1148
01:06:44.716 --> 01:06:48.136
But just to kind of briefly overview this, if you're not familiar with this assay,

1149
01:06:48.496 --> 01:06:52.306
essentially what it allows you to do is to take one PCR and convert it into

1150
01:06:52.436 --> 01:06:56.146
20,000 individual PCRs, where we can quantitate genomic changes

1151
01:06:56.396 --> 01:07:00.116
through fluorescent probes. And what I'm showing here is the CRLF2 locus.

1152
01:07:00.976 --> 01:07:02.596
And CRLF2 has three of these

1153
01:07:04.036 --> 01:07:07.495
CpG sites that can be recognized by AID, which are underlined in red.

1154
01:07:07.916 --> 01:07:11.836
And we essentially just designed a probe, FAM, TAMRA, and Cy5 to sit on top of

1155
01:07:11.876 --> 01:07:15.606
these. And essentially what would happen is if AID is acting at these sites, it

1156
01:07:15.616 --> 01:07:19.026
would mutate that site, the probe can no longer bind, and we can actually quantify

1157
01:07:19.036 --> 01:07:20.676
what's happening at that locus.

1158
01:07:21.696 --> 01:07:25.616
And so what we did was we had a dox-inducible AID system integrated into

1159
01:07:25.636 --> 01:07:28.856
our Nalm6 cells to actually see that this is actually the case.

1160
01:07:28.936 --> 01:07:32.736
So remarkably, what we can see is that whether we have increasing

1161
01:07:32.756 --> 01:07:36.496
expression of AID or prolonged exposure to AID, these

1162
01:07:36.536 --> 01:07:40.456
sites are in fact being mutated. And what we can see here is that the

1163
01:07:40.516 --> 01:07:44.496
TAMRA and the FAM sites seem to be much more highly affected than

1164
01:07:44.536 --> 01:07:45.436
the Cy5 site,

1165
01:07:46.596 --> 01:07:50.476
giving us a real solid clue that AID is a major driver for a lot of

1166
01:07:50.516 --> 01:07:50.696
these

1167
01:07:52.756 --> 01:07:53.556
translocations.

1168
01:07:54.356 --> 01:07:57.476
But of course, that doesn't really get to the heart of the disparity issue.

1169
01:07:57.556 --> 01:08:00.055
And for that, what we really have to do is turn to

1170
01:08:00.896 --> 01:08:04.316
actually further examining a lot more PH-like ALL samples.

1171
01:08:04.326 --> 01:08:08.296
So it is a rare cancer, but several study sites, particularly at MD

1172
01:08:08.396 --> 01:08:10.596
Anderson and St. Jude, have collected quite a bit of these.

1173
01:08:11.656 --> 01:08:15.456
But at UCI, we kind of have a unique catchment area in Orange County, which is

1174
01:08:15.496 --> 01:08:19.217
just north of here, where we have a predominantly Hispanic and Latino

1175
01:08:19.257 --> 01:08:23.047
population. And so what we really wanted to do was collect a lot of these

1176
01:08:23.076 --> 01:08:26.626
patient samples from the community and actually sequence them and try and

1177
01:08:26.677 --> 01:08:28.286
understand a little bit better if we can

1178
01:08:29.116 --> 01:08:30.556
know what's leading to this disparity.

1179
01:08:30.967 --> 01:08:34.376
And so this is a collaborative work at UCI with Angela Fleishman and Fabiola

1180
01:08:34.416 --> 01:08:38.276
Quintero-Rivera, and we've also reached out to Linda Bond at the Mayo Clinic to get

1181
01:08:38.316 --> 01:08:39.096
additional samples.

1182
01:08:40.445 --> 01:08:43.016
What I really want to point out with this slide, though, is this last column.

1183
01:08:43.476 --> 01:08:47.337
So what I'm showing here is essentially self-identified race or ethnicity, which we

1184
01:08:47.376 --> 01:08:50.276
have available for several of our studies at UCI.

1185
01:08:51.236 --> 01:08:53.476
But there's two problems with this column.

1186
01:08:53.556 --> 01:08:57.196
So one problem is, as has been kind of discussed here, there's a

1187
01:08:57.236 --> 01:09:01.126
difference between self-identified race and ethnicity and genetic ancestry.

1188
01:09:01.887 --> 01:09:05.656
And really it's been commonly shown that while there's social and economic factors

1189
01:09:05.696 --> 01:09:09.177
associated with race and ethnicity, there's no real biology there

1190
01:09:09.257 --> 01:09:12.916
associated with genetics. And so for that reason, we really need a genetic

1191
01:09:13.016 --> 01:09:14.076
ancestry

1192
01:09:15.096 --> 01:09:16.896
to weigh to study a lot of these populations.

1193
01:09:17.496 --> 01:09:20.856
And the second issue you can see is that several of these are unknown or not

1194
01:09:20.876 --> 01:09:21.337
reported.

1195
01:09:22.137 --> 01:09:25.776
So again, we're kind of not being able to really pick out a lot of the high-risk

1196
01:09:25.876 --> 01:09:29.116
patients here from the self-identified race and ethnicity.

1197
01:09:29.637 --> 01:09:31.856
And so this is a very common problem.

1198
01:09:31.896 --> 01:09:35.536
And even in the TCGA, which has been an amazing

1199
01:09:35.576 --> 01:09:38.677
resource, we can see that even within this database, there are

1200
01:09:39.016 --> 01:09:40.976
populations that are marked down as unknown.

1201
01:09:41.556 --> 01:09:44.797
And what this really creates is an issue, because if we could actually unlock the

1202
01:09:44.816 --> 01:09:48.236
genetic ancestry of some of these unknown or unreported ancestries,

1203
01:09:48.736 --> 01:09:52.177
we might actually be able to better understand a lot of the

1204
01:09:52.196 --> 01:09:55.936
disparities, not only in PH-like ALL, but several other types of cancers.

1205
01:09:56.896 --> 01:10:00.816
And so that was really the driving force behind this collaborative project

1206
01:10:00.825 --> 01:10:04.536
that we have at UCI, which is a collaboration between Salma

1207
01:10:04.556 --> 01:10:08.286
Masri, Marcus Selden, and is really driven by these two graduate students,

1208
01:10:08.416 --> 01:10:12.096
Angie Nguyen and Shannon Pfeiffer, who are fully computational in our labs and have

1209
01:10:12.116 --> 01:10:15.196
really delved into trying to understand this ancestry problem.

1210
01:10:15.976 --> 01:10:19.416
And essentially what we wanted to do was kind of go out and see in terms

1211
01:10:19.536 --> 01:10:22.985
of what's out there publicly available that we can use as

1212
01:10:23.696 --> 01:10:27.496
data to generate kind of an algorithm where we could plug in our whole genome

1213
01:10:27.556 --> 01:10:30.836
sequencing, our whole exome sequencing data, to essentially

1214
01:10:31.316 --> 01:10:34.616
reveal the genetic ancestry of the patients that we're seeing.

1215
01:10:35.056 --> 01:10:39.016
And one thing that we kind of ran into immediately with that is that some of

1216
01:10:39.036 --> 01:10:42.276
the publicly available data that's out there is very

1217
01:10:42.296 --> 01:10:45.896
heterogeneous. And so what I'm showing here is data from the Genome

1218
01:10:45.996 --> 01:10:49.735
Aggregation Database or gNOMAD, and this is from their build that used 1,000

1219
01:10:49.776 --> 01:10:52.736
genomes in the Human Genome Diversity project.

1220
01:10:53.836 --> 01:10:56.456
So we haven't seen any of these yet, but these are admixture plots.

1221
01:10:56.936 --> 01:11:00.916
And if you're unfamiliar with them, essentially within each of these vertical lines

1222
01:11:00.956 --> 01:11:03.856
is an individual person. And the colors indicate

1223
01:11:04.336 --> 01:11:08.136
essentially the genetic similarity they have to six major

1224
01:11:08.196 --> 01:11:10.156
population groups that we have outlined here.

1225
01:11:10.736 --> 01:11:14.296
And you can see in the gNOMAD cohorts, it kind of has a span from ones

1226
01:11:14.356 --> 01:11:18.276
that identify kind of more fully as this admixed American group to

1227
